member.summary:
Creates a list of
Steps to create the
Identify the Beginning of Each Cycle
The beginning of the cycle for a given phase is defined as the end of . The event log is queried to find the records where the Event Code is 9. Each instance of is indicated as the start of the cycle.
Identify the Change to Green for Each Cycle
During this step, the event log is queried to find the records where the Event Code . The duration from the beginning of the cycle to when the given phasechanges to green(total red interval) is calculated in reference to the first redevent (begin) of the cycle
Identify the Change to Yellow for Each Cycle
During this step, the event log is queried to find the record where the Event Code . The duration from the beginning of the cycle to when the given phase changes to yellow(total green interval) is calculated in reference to the first red event (begin) of the cycle
Identify the Change to Red at the End of Each Cycle
During this step, the event log is queried to find the records where the Event Code . The duration from the beginning of the cycle to when the given phase changes to red(yellow clearance interval) is calculated in reference to the firstred event (begin) of the cycle

member.summary: Identify and Adjust Vehicle Actuations During this step, the event log is queried to find detector activations for the subject phase (the records where the Event Code is and Event Parameter is a detector channel assigned to the subject phase). member.name: T:ATSPM.Application.Analysis.Workflows.ApproachDelayWorkflow
member.summary: Vehicle delay is a measure that is commonly modeled by agencies to identify whether intersection operations are acceptable.Using high-resolution data, this measure can be computed directly.For locations with high delay, particularly at uncongested locations, Location timing adjustments can help reduce wait times (1). Approach delay is a measure that integrates individual vehicle delay with volume to get an estimated sum of all vehicle delay on an approach.

member.name: T:ATSPM.Application.Analysis.Workflows.PreemptionDetailsWorkflow
member.summary: Preemption is the interruption of normal operations to serve a preferred vehicle(e.g., train, emergency vehicle). This measure can be used to determine if preemption events are occurring as intended. Preemption Details refers to the duration of preemption intervals for each preemption event. The type of interval information available depends on the type of preempt (i.e., rail or emergency vehicle) and the availability of certain inputs. Some potential intervals that can be tracked include entry delay, track clearance, gate down, dwell, time to service, max-out, and preempt input on/off (1).
